{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_amaryllis_ver01/data/sn88077226/00414210399/1949051001/0032.xml":{"full_text":"feage Two\np,\ntev-.-\nThe OHIO DAILY EXPRESS\nPublished every evening except Sunday by Paige H. Strickland at\n1007 Germantown street, Dayton 7, Ohio.- Phone HEmlock 1076\nAIGE H. STRICKLAND Editor and Publisher\nRUBY L. TAYLOR Business Manager\nRAYMOND SWANN Advertising Manager\nNATIONAL ADVERTISING, Interstate United Newspapers, Inc.\n545\n\"\"Ifth\nFortune magazine's polls, here re\ncently.\nRoper rtas speaking lor the\nAmerican Brotherhood in its lo\ncal campaign for funds at a con\nference of leaders in the'food and\ngrocery business in Hotel Sher\nman. itle of his address was '\"The\nCost of Prejudice to Business\",\n\"It is my contention today,\" he\nsaid, \"that we cannot afford to\ncontinue to discriminate against\nJews, Negroes, Catholics, Mexi\ncans, Nisei and others and still\nsay our economy is an efficient,\nfully productive system. We can\nnot afford to train a Negro car\npenter in a Nejfro engineers bat\ntalion during and then have him\nreturn to find that building houses\nfor other veterans is a \"white man'\njob\"\u2014that the carpenter's union\nwon't let him join. We cannot\nany longer afford to deprive a\nlarge number of our citizens of\nreasonable economic opportunity,\nsimply because a man's skin hap\npens to be darker than others,\nor his name is Greenberg or Scu\nderi.\nAvenue, New York, 17, New York\nRacial Prejudice Costs\nBusiness Says Roper\nCHICAGO, May 10. (ANP)\u2014\n\"There is a loss of real wealth to\nbusiness and to the people involved\nin racial and religious prejudice\"\ndeclared Elmer Roper, public re\nlations consultant and director of\nk\n\"Tocfey, democracy is on trial\nthroughout the world. We must\nprove to peoples of all races and\nreligions that our system, founded\non basic respect for the dignity\nof individuals, represents real\nfreedom from want and fear. Our\nway of life is competing with the\nRussian way.\n\"On our side, we have enormous\nadvantages. We have democratic\nprocesses, the right of free\nspeech, press, assembly and religi\nion. We can proudly say the ex\nistence of these liberties is some\nthing of the exception rather than\nthe rule in the history of the\nworld. W e also have the highest\nliving standards. Our laborers'\nreal income outstrip by an enor\nmous extent the real pay of work\ners in the any other country. Our\neconomic system, in spite of its\nmany flaws, still is the most pro\nductive and the wealthiest in the\nentire world.\nf*\n\"But in Europe snd in most of\nAsia we will be fighting a losing\nbattle as long as each lynching\nftnH race riot is carried in the\nheadlines of foreign newspapers,\n\u00abs long as our enemies can point\nout the fact that well over 10 per\ncent of our people are not full\npartners in our democracy.\"\nHitting directly at employers,\nhe declared that business in Amer\nica would stand to gain in terms\nof \"real wealth and over-all prof\nit\" by allowing the minority\npeoples to become \"full partners\nin our economy\".\n\"An elimination of discrimina\ntion in employment would help\nbusiness and the entire economy\nimmeasurably, would perhaps be\nenough to cushion a recession, and\nwould provide new limitless mar\nkets for new products which our\nindustrial genius could turn out.'\nHe cited the report of the Presi\ndent's Committee on Civil Rights\nas summing up the dilemna in\nthe American employment policies\nand added:\n\"In the end, the real wealth of\nour nation seems to come from\nour aatural and human resources\nand how ingeniously we use them.\nWhenever, a human being is pre\nvented from working at that task\nin which he is most productive,\nwe are wasting one of our two\nprime assets.\"\nThere was a bit of sqitwiittg on\npart of employers before he had\nfinished, but many agreed it was\nthe most forthright message local\nemployers had ever received from\na recognized expert.\nGl Sentenced to Die\nCHICAGO, May 10. (ANP)\u2014\nA Chicago GI, Pvt. James W. Har\nris, 20, has been sentenced to\ndeath in Tokyo for slaying a Jap\nanese girl, Shimako Mitsuhashi,\n22, last January.\nHis case will come up foir re\nview soon to Brig. Gen. Crtimp\nGarvin, commanding general of\nYokohama. Pvt| Harris denied\nany connection with the butcher\nknife slaying, but the general\ncourts martial convicted him.\nKKK's Stronghold,\nAtlanta, Bans Masks\nATLANTA, May 10. (ANP)\u2014\nThis city, strongliold of the Ku\nKlux Klan, now has an ordinance\nwhich makes the wearing of masks\nin public, except for for festive\noccasions, an offense punishable\nby a fine of $200 and 30 days in\njail. The ordinance was approved\n17-0 by the city* council here last\nweek.\nThe lata was introduced by Ar\n(continued on page 3)\nOHld DAILY EXPRESS\nCharles Wilson\nAwarded for Work\nOn Vivil Rights in 1948\nWASHINGTON, May 10. (ANP)\nThere woul^ be no need for civil\neights legislation if the American\npeople had proper education, dis\nposition, compassion, tolerance,\nand courage declare'd Charles E.\nWilson, president of the General\nElectric company,.at a civil rights\nbanquet given by the American\nVeterans committee, last Saturday\nnight.\nIn referring to the report made\nby the President's Civil Rights\ncommittee, of which he was chair\nman,^ Wilson said \"if the entire\nbatch of recommendations were\nput into action, we should still\nhave nothing but the skeleton of\ncivil rights protection. The flesh\nand blood to clothe those bones lie\nin the hearts and minds of all Am\nericans, and without this there is\nnothing.\"\n\"I don't think we can ever legis\nlate our way out of color and rac\nial discrimination, out of unfair\nemployment practices, or out of\nreligious bigotry. Force never\nchanged anybdy's mind, but edu\ncation and understanding have\nwon a lot of victories, even though\nthey take longer,\" he related.\nWilson was one of the three re\ncipients of awards giy\u00a3Jft by AVC\nfor outstanding achievement. The\ncitation was presented him by Gil\nbert Harrison, new chairman of\nthe Press-Radio wing of the com\nmittee, for having the greatest\ncontribution for civil rights in\nAmerica during 1948.\nAnother award was made to Dr.\nE. B. Henderson, head of the de\npartment of physical education\nand health in the Negro schools in\nthe District of Columbia. Dr. Hen\nderson is also an executive of the\nNAACP both in the District and in\nFalls Church, Va. chairman of the\nboard of governors of YMCA and\nvice president of the Council of\nCivil Rights in the nation's capital.\nMADAM LAMAR\n5724 West Third Street\nPkone ME 7607\nReader and Advistor\nSpecial Reading\n$1.00\nI give never failing advice\nupon all matters of life, such\nas love, courtship, marriage, di\nvorce, business transaction* of\nall kinds. I never fail to reunite\nthe separated, cause speedy and\nhappy marriages, overcome en\nemies, rivals, lover's quarrels,\nevil habits, stumbling blocks,\nand bad luck of all loads. I\nlift you out of sorrow and\ntroubles and start you on the\npath of happiness and prosper\nity. There is no heart se Dad\nor home so dreary that\nThe third award was presented\nto Herbert L. Block, editorial car\ntoonist for the Washington Post.\n'Herblock'' was a Pulitzer prize\nwinner in 1942, and this year won\nhonorable mention in ihe Heywood\nBroun Memorial award.\nDr. Henderson's award was\ngiven for \"his untiring efforts to\nfocus public attention on discrim\nination and segregation in the Dis\ntrict of Columbia public school re\ncreational facilities and in the\nMetropolitan Police Boys club for\nserving as a litigant in the suit\nto end discrimination in the Na\ntional theatrefor aiding the suc\ncessful effort to end segregation\nin the National Zoological cafe\nteria for aiding in the planning of\na stadium to serve patrons of all\nraces and for constant champion\nship of the cause of civil rights\nabove and beyond the call of duty.\nDr. Henderson was cited by the\nGreater Washington Area of AVC\nfor \"his inspiring contribution to\nfreedom in the if. S.\"\n\"Herblock\" was cite'd by the\nGifted Reader\nLUCK! MADAME LEE\nFirst Time Here\nReader and Adviser\nGives advice on all affairs of life,\nbusiness, love, marriage, divorce,\nhealth and family affairs. Price\nin reach of all. Located in trailer\nat city limits of Franklin, Ohio,\nnorth on U. S. 25. Look for sign\nat Smith's. Trailer Camp. Hours:\n10 a. m. until 10 p. m.\nLucky Days.\nof any kind.\nI\ncan\u00ad\nnot bring sunshine in it. In\nfact, no matter what may be\nyour hope, fear or ambition, I\n'guarantee to tell it all before\nyou utter a word to me and\nafter I am\nfluiihit\nif you are\nnot entirely MtMied and jt\ndo not faithfully fatttl every\nclaipi atore,\n4mi\nnot a\nrom pair me\nYour Name U--.r.\nAddress ...i.\u2014\nNumber of Insertions....\nShall we use Key No.?\nTuesday, May 10, 1949\nPress-Radio wing fer \"his unerr-\"\ning ability to present cartoons\nwhich expose with wit and wisdoms\nthe absurdity of the demagogtfe\nand the bigot.\"\nPresiding\nkt\nthe banquet was\nSam Zagroria,. retiring chairman\"\nof the Press-Radio wing of AVC*\nBUY U. S. BONDS\nAND STAMPS\nPRESCRIPTIONS\nFAITHFULLY\nCOMPOUNDED\nYon can depend a pan Thrifty\nPharmacist* to compound\nyour Jocter'i prescription as\nactljr as it is written.\nOnly, the finest choinicals rt\nused in Thrifty prc\u00abtr'(t!6\nto assort yon every benefit\nyonr doctor intended yon to\nbate from the medicine he has\nprescribed.\nFor Truthful Advice on All Affairs\nOf Life\u2014See\nMRS. DONNA\nIf you are worried, unhappy, discontented, depressed, and\nfeel that you need some advice, come to some one who can give\nyou reliable advice on life.\ni\nConcerning Lucky Dates and\nTells you how to overcome all evils, apd bad luck\nResults Guaranteed.\nDon't compare me with Imitators or Impersonators. My\nwork is a gift of God. I do what others claim to do. No letters\nanswered, no house call made.\nPermanently located i